# Challenge 1 — Closure & Continuity

## Situation

A meaningful volume of customer frustration and repeat contact behavior appeared to be associated with how conversations concluded.

While the underlying lifecycle logic was functioning as intended, customer expectations frequently differed from system expectations regarding when an interaction was complete.

## Analysis

Several potential causes were considered:

* Lifecycle rules
* Automation logic
* User inactivity assumptions
* Communication gaps
* Platform constraints

The strongest signal pointed toward expectation misalignment rather than technical failure.

The system considered interactions complete.

Customers often did not.

## Approach

I redesigned the closure experience around continuity and confidence rather than solely lifecycle logic.

The focus was on:

* Lifecycle transparency
* Closure communication
* Continuity signals
* Expectation setting
* Confidence in conversation status

## Outcome

The closure experience became more predictable and understandable.

### Business Impact

* Reduced repeat contact behavior
* Reduced customer effort
* Improved confidence in support continuity
* Improved overall experience reliability

