# Challenge 2 — Escalation & Human Handover

## Situation

Escalation represented one of the highest-friction moments in the customer journey.

Customers frequently became uncertain about:

* Whether escalation had succeeded
* Whether progress was being made
* What would happen next
* Whether context would be retained

## Analysis

A common assumption was that operational performance was the primary driver of dissatisfaction.

However, analysis suggested frustration often emerged before operational delays became significant.

The issue was confidence and expectation management.

## Key Decision

Treat escalation as a trust problem rather than a queue problem.

## Approach

I redesigned escalation communication around:

* State-aware messaging
* Context-sensitive notifications
* Progress visibility
* Expectation management
* Reduced communication noise

The objective was not more communication.

The objective was more meaningful communication.

## Outcome

The escalation experience became more predictable and understandable.

### Business Impact

* Reduced escalation-related frustration
* Reduced duplicate requests
* Improved customer confidence
* Improved assisted support experience

---

# Challenge 3 — Fragmented Journeys

## Situation

Customer requests were frequently handled as isolated interactions despite being connected parts of a broader customer goal.

This created unnecessary effort and reduced continuity.

## Analysis

The experience optimized for intent completion.

Customers optimized for outcomes.

This disconnect created friction throughout the journey.

## Key Decision

Reframe support interactions from intent resolution to journey progression.

## Approach

I designed an orchestration model focused on continuity and contextual progression.

The redesign introduced:

* Intent chaining
* Context preservation
* Journey progression logic
* Guided next-best actions
* Connected support pathways

## Outcome

The support experience became more cohesive and goal-oriented.

### Business Impact

* Reduced customer effort
* Improved continuity
* Improved task progression
* Increased perceived system intelligence

