# Reflection & Lessons Learned

The most important lesson from this work is that customer experience failures are often misdiagnosed.

Viewed individually, metrics such as inactivity, abandonment, bounce-off behavior, duplicate requests, escalation friction, and closure events appeared to represent separate issues.

Viewed together, they revealed a consistent pattern of customers losing confidence during moments of uncertainty.

This fundamentally changed how I approach service design.

Rather than starting with interactions, I now start by understanding where confidence breaks down across the system.

The highest-leverage opportunities frequently exist not within individual features, but within the relationships between them.

This project reinforced a principle that continues to guide my work:

> Trust is not a feature.
